 MBOMBELA – At a meeting of the Provincial Executive Council (PEC) on Wednesday it was briefed on Mpumalanga’s strategy to deal with the current malaria outbreak as 8 000 cases were reported, with 85 deaths occurring between April 2017 and January 2018. According to the briefing the outbreak is most intense in the areas around the Kruger National Park as well as Nkomazi and Bushbuckridge municipalities. Also read: You probably did not know this about malaria The PEC tasked the provincial Department of Health to develop a clear plan which aims to improve awareness campaigns and train community-development workers so they are equipped with basic testing kits to assist those suspected to have contracted malaria. The PEC also received a report on the status of listeriosis in the province, where eight deaths among the 35 patients affected from January 2017 to January 2018 were recorded. Also read: The silent killer strikes again At least two people are still in provincial hospitals due to the serious bacterial infection caused by eating food contaminated with listeriosis bacteria. It is widely distributed in nature and can be found in soil, water, animals and vegetation. Pregnant women, newborns, the elderly and people with compromised immune systems are susceptible to the disease. Also read: Beware of unapproved malaria drugs The council has reiterated its call on the department to strengthen its awareness campaigns in order to alert citizens about the dangers of listeriosis.